Package com.cafean.client.analysis

Class Category<T extends AbstractComponent>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.cafean.client.analysis.Category<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the AbstractComponent extension type which is managed by this category. This is useful for components which are concrete types as this is used in the types returned by the findBy and component/component list creation methods.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Comparable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    SearchCategory
    public class Category<T extends AbstractComponent>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable, java.lang.Cloneable
    A node in a hierarchy of component types within a model.

    Categories are used to represent each specific component type. Each of these categories can also have parent and child Categories representing subsets and supersets of component types.

    Any given model should have a Category for each of its component types and a root Category for each component or subset of components that are to be manipulated by the ModelEditor user interface.

    WARNING: Do not check Category equivalence with ==. Use equals(java.lang.Object) instead as derivative plugins may need to replace a defined Category.

    An abbreviated example of creating a hierarchy of Category objects: 

          public static final Category CAT_PIPE = new Category("Pipes", "/cfnplugin/test/pipe.png");
      public static final Category CAT_PUMP = new Category("Pumps", "/cfnplugin/test/pump.png");
      private static final Category[] HYDROS = { CAT_PIPE, CAT_PUMP };
      public static final Category CAT_HYDRAULIC = new Category("Hydraulic Components",
                                                                "/cfnplugin/test/hydro.png");
                                                                HYDRAULIC_COMPONENTS );
      private static final Category[] COMPONENTS = { CAT_HYDRAULIC, CAT_CONTROL_SYS };
    With the above example, getCategories would then be overridden like this: 
          public Category[] getCategories() 
      {
          Category[] supers = super.getCategories();
          Category[] categories = new Category[COMPONENTS.length+supers.length];
          System.arraycopy(COMPONENTS, 0, categories, 0, COMPONENTS.length );
          System.arraycopy(supers, 0, categories, COMPONENTS.length, supers.length );
          return categories;
      }

        public Category​(java.lang.String name,
                boolean visual,
                boolean ordered,
                java.lang.String iconPath,
                java.lang.Class owner)
        Creates a new Category with the given name, with the given visual and ordered status.

        The given owner is the class that should be used as a point of reference for loading this Category's icon. This parameter is not necessary unless the icon must be loaded by a ClassLoader other than those used to load MEPlugin and Display Bean instances. In all other cases this parameter should either not be used or be passed a null.

        Parameters:
        name - a String containing the name of the category
        visual - true if this category contains components that can be represented in a 2D View.
        ordered - if true, components in this Category hides their component number, and use it only for sorting in the Navigator.
        iconPath - a String containing the full source path to the icon
        owner - the Class that should be used as a point of reference for loading the icon.

      • and

        public static Category[] and​(java.lang.Object... categories)
        Creates a flat category array from the given categories, arrays of categories, and collections of categories. This method is intended to reduce the noise level of static Category and SearchCategory instantiations.
        Parameters:
        categories - the categories, category arrays, and collections of categories that should be combined
        Returns:
        a Category[] containing all of the given categories
        Throws:
        java.lang.ArrayStoreException - if the runtime type of any given element isn't either a Category, an array of categories, or a Collection of categories.
